{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"ottoman-empire-rise","type":"era","content":{"title":"Rise of the Ottoman Empire","date_label":"1299 – 1453","description":"Founded by **Osman I** around 1299 CE, the Ottoman state grew from a small Anatolian principality into one of the most powerful empires in the world. Under a succession of capable sultans, Ottoman forces steadily expanded across Anatolia, into the Balkans, and eventually across the Bosphorus.\n\nThe defining moment of the early Ottoman era was the conquest of **Constantinople in 1453** under Sultan **Mehmed II** — ending the Byzantine Empire and transforming the ancient city into the Ottoman capital. This event so shocked the Christian world that it is traditionally used to mark the end of the Middle Ages.\n\nBy 1453 the Ottomans controlled the strategic crossroads between Europe and Asia, and would continue expanding for another century, besieging Vienna twice and controlling much of the Mediterranean world.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["ottoman","mehmed","constantinople","anatolia","medieval","islamic"],"sources":[{"title":"Ottoman Empire — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/place/Ottoman-Empire"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"1299","end_value":"1453","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":870,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"middle-east-europe"}}}
